<bioghist encodinganalog="545">
<p>Between 1925 and 1926 the University of Michigan swim coach Matt Mann started The Flounders, a water polo team for male faculty members. The members consistently met three times week, Monday, Wednesday, and Friday at noon at the Michigan Union pool, where they would play a quick game, then head off to a group lunch at the Union. The Flounders became known for their lack of definitive rules, rough playing style, and for not keeping an official score. When a member's name appeared in print that player was obligated to buy coffee or, as the updated rules state, ice-cream or both for the other members. Undergraduate students who were members of the swim team and sons of members were allowed to join the team, as long as they could make it through one game, which usually lasted half an hour and could involve being scratched, injured, or held under water for up to five minutes at a time.</p>
</bioghist>

<scopecontent encodinganalog="520"><p>The collection is comprised of two series; Administration and Background Information, and Other Media. The bulk of the records are in the Administration series, which contains information pertaining to the history of the organization, fundraising efforts by the Flounders for a score board, memorials, and bills for annual charges for supplies and rental of space. The Other Media series primarily documents random weekly games, team pictures, and the planting of a memorial tree in 1983 for deceased Flounder member John Slocum. There are also several CD-ROMS that contain images of members and miscellaneous clippings. A DVD is included that was created for the 75th anniversary of the founding of the Flounders in 2003. The paper records accumulated during the making of the anniversary DVD, which include typed captions for images, are within the administration series. A VHS Tape is also included as part of the collection that contains material documented in 2002. </p></scopecontent>

